        </div>

        <div class="long-division-container" id="long-division-container">
          <h3>Long Division Steps</h3>
          <p class="step-desc">Here is how you get the decimal by dividing the numerator by the denominator:</p>
          <div class="division-table" id="division-table">
            <!-- Dynamically populated -->
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="educational-section">
      <h2>Understanding Fractions and Decimals</h2>
      <div class="edu-grid">
        <div class="edu-card">
          <div class="edu-icon">➗</div>
          <h3>How to Convert Fractions to Decimals</h3>
          <p>Converting a fraction to a decimal is straightforward: you divide the top number (numerator) by the bottom number (denominator). The fraction bar literally means "divided by". For example, the fraction 3/4 means 3 divided by 4.</p>
          <p>When using a calculator, simply type the numerator, hit the division key, type the denominator, and press equals. If you are doing it manually, you use long division, adding decimal points and zeroes to the dividend as needed.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-card">
          <div class="edu-icon">🛑</div>
          <h3>Terminating Decimals</h3>
          <p>A terminating decimal is one that eventually ends. It doesn't go on forever. When you divide the numerator by the denominator, you eventually reach a remainder of zero.</p>
          <p>A fascinating mathematical rule is that a fraction (in simplest form) will only result in a terminating decimal if the prime factors of its denominator are exclusively 2s and/or 5s. For instance, 1/8 (since 8 = 2×2×2) terminates at 0.125.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-card">
          <div class="edu-icon">🔁</div>
          <h3>Repeating Decimals</h3>
          <p>A repeating decimal continues infinitely, with a specific sequence of digits repeating over and over again. This happens when your long division keeps reaching the same remainder, putting you into an infinite loop.</p>
          <p>For example, 1/3 = 0.3333... and 1/7 = 0.142857142857... These are often denoted by writing a line (vinculum) over the repeating digits: 0.<span>142857</span>.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-card">
          <div class="edu-icon">💯</div>
          <h3>Fractions to Percentages</h3>
          <p>Once you have converted a fraction to a decimal, turning it into a percentage is the easiest step! You simply multiply the decimal by 100 (which moves the decimal point two places to the right) and add a percent sign (%).</p>
          <p>If you have 5/8, which is 0.625 as a decimal, multiplying by 100 gives you 62.5%.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

