        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">How do you convert a fraction to a decimal?</h3>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>To convert a fraction to a decimal, divide the numerator (the top number) by the denominator (the bottom number). For example, to convert 3/4 to a decimal, divide 3 by 4 to get 0.75.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">What is a repeating decimal?</h3>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>A repeating decimal is a decimal representation of a number whose digits are periodic. This means that a sequence of one or more digits repeats infinitely. For example, 1/3 as a decimal is 0.333..., where the 3 repeats forever. It is often written with a line over the repeating part.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">How do I turn 1/8 into a decimal?</h3>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>Divide 1 by 8 using long division or a calculator. 1 divided by 8 is 0.125. The fraction 1/8 terminates because its denominator is a power of 2.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">What are terminating decimals?</h3>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>A terminating decimal is a decimal that ends. It has a finite number of digits. Examples include 0.5 (which is 1/2), 0.25 (which is 1/4), and 0.125 (which is 1/8). Fractions result in terminating decimals if their denominator's only prime factors are 2 and 5.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">How to write a mixed number as a decimal?</h3>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>To convert a mixed number to a decimal, keep the whole number part as it is, and convert the fractional part to a decimal by dividing the numerator by the denominator. Then, add the whole number and the decimal together. For instance, for 2 1/2, convert 1/2 to 0.5, resulting in 2.5.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
